00:34:26.739 --> 00:34:31.850
I mean, think about if child
poverty dropped by that amount,

00:34:31.850 --> 00:34:32.350
right?

00:34:32.350 --> 00:34:33.730
Or expanded by that amount.

00:34:33.730 --> 00:34:37.210
Any sort of social metric that
went up as much as crime did,

00:34:37.210 --> 00:34:39.570
and then went down
as much, would

00:34:39.570 --> 00:34:42.909
have huge political and
social consequences.

00:34:42.909 --> 00:34:44.590
Now, the issue
partly-- and there's

00:34:44.590 --> 00:34:46.381
a chapter in the book
about broken windows.

00:34:48.790 --> 00:34:50.590
At the core of the
issue is the fact

00:34:50.590 --> 00:34:55.000
that crime drops
between '92 and 2014.

00:34:55.000 --> 00:34:58.210
And it's one of the great
sociological mysteries

00:34:58.210 --> 00:34:59.710
of our time.

00:34:59.710 --> 00:35:01.060
We just don't know.

00:35:01.060 --> 00:35:02.950
It probably comes
down to a layering

00:35:02.950 --> 00:35:04.630
of a variety of factors.

00:35:04.630 --> 00:35:07.300
There's a demographic
component to it.

00:35:07.300 --> 00:35:09.730
In the beginning, the
increase in incarceration

00:35:09.730 --> 00:35:13.510
probably does part of it, too.

00:35:13.510 --> 00:35:15.430
If you think of a
thought experiment,

00:35:15.430 --> 00:35:20.290
if you took a society, and then
you put every male 18 to 24

00:35:20.290 --> 00:35:25.040
in prison, the
crime would go down.

00:35:25.040 --> 00:35:27.100
It would.

00:35:27.100 --> 00:35:30.430
That would obviously be
unjustifiable across any sort

00:35:30.430 --> 00:35:32.230
of moral, political framework.

00:35:32.230 --> 00:35:33.610
But as a raw--

00:35:33.610 --> 00:35:38.560
and there's neighborhoods
where that basically was done.

00:35:38.560 --> 00:35:42.610
So incarceration probably
played some role.

00:35:42.610 --> 00:35:46.840
There is the
argument about lead,

00:35:46.840 --> 00:35:50.140
that lead played a huge role
in the increase in crime,

00:35:50.140 --> 00:35:54.670
and then the unleaded gasoline
and catalytic converters

00:35:54.670 --> 00:35:56.126
went down.

00:35:56.126 --> 00:35:58.000
And then there's the
question about policing.

00:35:58.000 --> 00:36:00.370
So the reason I'm
laying the groundwork

00:36:00.370 --> 00:36:06.670
is because the story, which is
not a crazy story that I think

00:36:06.670 --> 00:36:08.200
generations of
politicians, police

00:36:08.200 --> 00:36:09.910
officials, and the
public have learned,

00:36:09.910 --> 00:36:14.380
is that the bad old days happen,
and then Bill Bratton came in,

00:36:14.380 --> 00:36:17.710
and they started broken-windows
policing and Rudy Giuliani,

00:36:17.710 --> 00:36:19.480
and that was spread
across the country.

00:36:19.480 --> 00:36:21.340
And that caused
the crime decline.

00:36:21.340 --> 00:36:23.590
And so now you've got this
kind of, it's almost this--

00:36:23.590 --> 00:36:26.350
I describe it in the book
as cargo cult thinking.

00:36:26.350 --> 00:36:28.616
It's like rain dance.

00:36:28.616 --> 00:36:29.990
There's the cause
and the effect.

00:36:29.990 --> 00:36:34.780
So it's like you have to devote
yourself to the crime gods.

00:36:34.780 --> 00:36:36.790
Because if you don't,
then the bad old days

00:36:36.790 --> 00:36:39.270
are going to come back.

00:36:39.270 --> 00:36:43.540
And in some ways,
I understand why

00:36:43.540 --> 00:36:45.790
particularly police
professionals who oversaw

00:36:45.790 --> 00:36:47.730
that period think they did it.

00:36:47.730 --> 00:36:49.000
i would think I did it, too.

00:36:49.000 --> 00:36:50.830
And there's no
question, I think,

00:36:50.830 --> 00:36:54.950
that some policing is
better than others.

00:36:54.950 --> 00:36:57.790
But I also think we
have to recognize

00:36:57.790 --> 00:36:59.800
that a lot of
nonpolicing factors

00:36:59.800 --> 00:37:02.380
were driving that,
which brings us

00:37:02.380 --> 00:37:04.270
to the great
stop-and-frisk experiment.

00:37:04.270 --> 00:37:07.627
Because the warning,
when the city settled

00:37:07.627 --> 00:37:10.210
the stop-and-frisk lawsuit, from
people like Ray Kelly and all

00:37:10.210 --> 00:37:13.750
sorts of folks was the bad
old days are gonna come back.

00:37:13.750 --> 00:37:14.590
And they haven't.

00:37:14.590 --> 00:37:16.180
So New York City--

00:37:16.180 --> 00:37:19.090
and that's an environment in
which a lot of top 25 cities

00:37:19.090 --> 00:37:24.070
have seen really worrying
rises in homicide,

00:37:24.070 --> 00:37:26.320
seriously upsetting rises--

00:37:26.320 --> 00:37:32.380
Chicago, Baltimore, Cleveland,
St. Louis, Milwaukee.

00:37:32.380 --> 00:37:33.280
New York's gone down.

00:37:35.817 --> 00:37:37.900
But it gets to this really
deep, fundamental point

00:37:37.900 --> 00:37:40.024
because you're seeing the
politics of law and order

00:37:40.024 --> 00:37:43.710
in those cities go right back
to the politics of law and order

00:37:43.710 --> 00:37:47.290
in the 1970s.

00:37:47.290 --> 00:37:48.160
TORRENCE BOONE: Yes.

00:37:48.160 --> 00:37:50.493
AUDIENCE: I was wondering if
you could talk a little bit

00:37:50.493 --> 00:37:53.300
about the Philadelphia DA
primary that just happened

00:37:53.300 --> 00:37:55.364
and what do you think
the significance of that

00:37:55.364 --> 00:37:57.280
going forward and whether
that's a model for--

00:37:57.280 --> 00:37:58.160
CHRIS HAYES: I'm glad
you brought that up.

00:37:58.160 --> 00:38:00.010
I mortifyingly
misspoke this morning

00:38:00.010 --> 00:38:01.390
and said it was the election,
not the primary, when

00:38:01.390 --> 00:38:02.320
I was speaking at Osborne.

00:38:02.320 --> 00:38:03.361
And then someone told me.

00:38:03.361 --> 00:38:06.940
And I wanted to crawl
into a corner and die.

00:38:06.940 --> 00:38:11.330
So 90% of my cognitive
energy for the last six hours

00:38:11.330 --> 00:38:14.350
has gone to that.

00:38:14.350 --> 00:38:16.180
Why did I make that mistake?

00:38:16.180 --> 00:38:18.400
It's a primary.

00:38:18.400 --> 00:38:21.620
Now I can get that back.

00:38:21.620 --> 00:38:25.720
So I tell people all the time
on book talks, what can I do?

00:38:25.720 --> 00:38:28.516
And the thing I say is, we
focus on the federal government.

00:38:28.516 --> 00:38:29.890
But the criminal
justice system--

00:38:29.890 --> 00:38:32.260
and this is a point
that's really made well--

00:38:32.260 --> 00:38:34.480
It's made well in James
Forman's great book,

00:38:34.480 --> 00:38:36.740
"Locking Up Our Own,"
which I recommend,

00:38:36.740 --> 00:38:39.340
and "Locked In" by John
Pfaff, which is out-- which

00:38:39.340 --> 00:38:41.740
is that there is no single
criminal justice system.

00:38:41.740 --> 00:38:44.890
It's literally thousands of
systems, like county sheriffs,

00:38:44.890 --> 00:38:48.070
municipal DA's, all these
different interlocking systems

00:38:48.070 --> 00:38:50.290
at the local level, and
a lot of elected leaders

00:38:50.290 --> 00:38:54.324
who are elected in super
low-turnout elections, which

00:38:54.324 --> 00:38:55.990
in some ways is the
good news because it

00:38:55.990 --> 00:38:57.940
means you have a lever.

00:38:57.940 --> 00:38:59.740
If you devote
yourself to working

00:38:59.740 --> 00:39:01.840
on these issues in
local elections,

00:39:01.840 --> 00:39:03.234
you can have a huge impact.

00:39:03.234 --> 00:39:04.900
And the Philadelphia
primary is probably

00:39:04.900 --> 00:39:07.210
the most stunning
example of that so far.

00:39:07.210 --> 00:39:11.260
A guy named Larry Krasner, who
is a sort of notorious lefty

00:39:11.260 --> 00:39:15.250
lawyer of Philadelphia--
he's the lawyer that is there

00:39:15.250 --> 00:39:19.060
when a bunch of protesters
are arrested at a protest

00:39:19.060 --> 00:39:21.610
to bail them out.

00:39:21.610 --> 00:39:24.940
He has no prosecutorial
experience.

00:39:24.940 --> 00:39:29.980
And the police union hates
him and, in the manner

00:39:29.980 --> 00:39:34.642
of police unions everywhere,
was not shy about saying that.

00:39:34.642 --> 00:39:36.475
Police unions tend to
speak in one register.

00:39:36.475 --> 00:39:39.058
I don't know if you've noticed
this from official police union

00:39:39.058 --> 00:39:41.260
statements.

00:39:41.260 --> 00:39:45.890
And Krasner won this
primary explicitly

00:39:45.890 --> 00:39:48.770
on a program of reform.

00:39:48.770 --> 00:39:51.590
He's not the first sort
of reformer DA to win.

00:39:51.590 --> 00:39:55.070
There's a woman in Orlando
who won similarly and is now

00:39:55.070 --> 00:39:57.170
locked in a battle with
the state Republicans who

00:39:57.170 --> 00:39:59.420
want to take her power away
because she said she's not

00:39:59.420 --> 00:40:00.850
going to use the death penalty.

00:40:00.850 --> 00:40:03.360
There's a woman in
Cook County, Illinois,

00:40:03.360 --> 00:40:05.240
who grew up in
[INAUDIBLE] who also

00:40:05.240 --> 00:40:09.800
won and unseated the
district attorney--

00:40:09.800 --> 00:40:12.050
or I guess in Illinois,
it's the state's attorney--

00:40:12.050 --> 00:40:15.484
who had sort of been implicated
in the Laquan McDonald coverup.

00:40:15.484 --> 00:40:17.900
So this is something that's
happening in different places.

00:40:17.900 --> 00:40:21.800
Krasner, I would say, is
the most remarkable example.

00:40:21.800 --> 00:40:27.550
And he's now got a general
election ahead of him,

00:40:27.550 --> 00:40:30.170
a thing I didn't
say this morning.

00:40:30.170 --> 00:40:33.380
And he's now got a general
election ahead of him.

00:40:33.380 --> 00:40:37.610
And that's gonna be a
really fascinating fight.

00:40:37.610 --> 00:40:42.170
And what's going to be even more
interesting is if he wins, OK.

00:40:42.170 --> 00:40:45.950
What does the rubber
hitting the road look like?

00:40:45.950 --> 00:40:47.510
Talking about all
this is one thing.

00:40:47.510 --> 00:40:50.930
But the reason that there's a
lot of hope around prosecutors

00:40:50.930 --> 00:40:53.960
is because a lot of empirical
work that's been done

00:40:53.960 --> 00:40:57.020
shows that prosecutors more
than any other single actors

00:40:57.020 --> 00:41:00.200
in the system were the ones
driving mass incarceration.

00:41:00.200 --> 00:41:01.610
It wasn't mandatory minimums.

00:41:01.610 --> 00:41:03.560
It wasn't statutes being passed.

00:41:03.560 --> 00:41:06.500
It was prosecutors
using their discretion

00:41:06.500 --> 00:41:09.380
to charge five crimes
for a max of 20

00:41:09.380 --> 00:41:11.175
rather than one crime
for a max of five.

00:41:11.175 --> 00:41:13.300
And when they charged five
crimes with a max of 20,

00:41:13.300 --> 00:41:15.500
and they plea down
to 15 or 12, you've

00:41:15.500 --> 00:41:17.810
got someone who's doing
a 12-year bid as opposed

00:41:17.810 --> 00:41:19.520
to a one-year bid.

00:41:19.520 --> 00:41:22.332
That's the latitude
that prosecutors have,

00:41:22.332 --> 00:41:24.665
and the latitude they have
in a system in which, again--

00:41:24.665 --> 00:41:26.550
you've got to remind
yourself this all the time,

00:41:26.550 --> 00:41:27.950
particularly if you're not
someone who's spending a lot

00:41:27.950 --> 00:41:29.630
of time in the criminal
justice system--

00:41:29.630 --> 00:41:34.190
the criminal justice system is
a factory for producing pleas.

00:41:36.747 --> 00:41:38.830
Your input are arrests,
and the outputs are pleas.

00:41:41.410 --> 00:41:43.730
There are no trials in America.

00:41:43.730 --> 00:41:45.580
It's a rounding error, trials.

00:41:45.580 --> 00:41:47.620
All the pop culture
representations

00:41:47.620 --> 00:41:51.190
of American criminal justice
are the rounding error.

00:41:51.190 --> 00:41:54.850
What it is is it's Lucy
with the chocolates.

00:41:54.850 --> 00:41:59.080
That's a night in court
in any major municipality.

00:41:59.080 --> 00:42:02.070
And so because it's a machine
that produces pleas out

00:42:02.070 --> 00:42:05.830
of the input of arrests,
these two main fulcrums

00:42:05.830 --> 00:42:08.710
are what you're
pleaing to, which

00:42:08.710 --> 00:42:12.010
is the knob that the
prosecutors can turn,

00:42:12.010 --> 00:42:13.510
and how many arrests
you're getting,

00:42:13.510 --> 00:42:16.000
which is the knob
the police can turn.

00:42:16.000 --> 00:42:19.000
So those are two of the
regulators on that system.

00:42:19.000 --> 00:42:21.470
And those are two places--

00:42:21.470 --> 00:42:23.170
what are police
arresting folks for,

00:42:23.170 --> 00:42:26.624
and what are prosecutors
charging and accepting pleas?

00:42:26.624 --> 00:42:28.540
TORRENCE BOONE: And those
prosecutors, though,

00:42:28.540 --> 00:42:31.600
are connected to the
political machine.

00:42:31.600 --> 00:42:34.300
CHRIS HAYES: I mean,
Europe thinks it's nuts

00:42:34.300 --> 00:42:36.970
that we elect prosecutors.

00:42:36.970 --> 00:42:37.900
Right?

00:42:37.900 --> 00:42:43.780
I mean, it's literally
in the Bible, right?

00:42:43.780 --> 00:42:49.630
The scene where Jesus is killed
is essentially the punishment

00:42:49.630 --> 00:42:52.180
being put up to the crowd.

00:42:52.180 --> 00:42:55.380
Pontius Plate's like,
what should I do?

00:42:55.380 --> 00:42:56.380
We want Barabbas, right?

00:42:56.380 --> 00:43:01.210
Now The crowd, literally,
it's like the iconic example

00:43:01.210 --> 00:43:04.570
of the crowd gone
wild, is in the context

00:43:04.570 --> 00:43:08.140
of a crowd selecting a
punishment for Jesus Christ.

00:43:08.140 --> 00:43:12.220
But that's basically
what DA elections are.

00:43:12.220 --> 00:43:15.910
We put people
politically in charge

00:43:15.910 --> 00:43:19.390
of making these decisions
that in other systems

00:43:19.390 --> 00:43:22.390
are insulated from
democratic input

00:43:22.390 --> 00:43:25.030
and are appointed
like a judiciary

00:43:25.030 --> 00:43:27.700
and probably produce far
less punitive outcomes

00:43:27.700 --> 00:43:28.867
for that reason.

00:43:28.867 --> 00:43:30.700
TORRENCE BOONE: We'll
take another question,

00:43:30.700 --> 00:43:33.970
but I do want to come
back to what can we do?

00:43:33.970 --> 00:43:36.400
What advice would you give
us individually and as

00:43:36.400 --> 00:43:38.206
an organization in
terms of addressing

00:43:38.206 --> 00:43:39.080
some of these issues?

00:43:39.080 --> 00:43:39.579
Yes.

00:43:39.579 --> 00:43:41.860
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:43:41.860 --> 00:43:45.590
I feel like the
Democrats have not

00:43:45.590 --> 00:43:50.390
been particularly good
at making racial justice

00:43:50.390 --> 00:43:53.320
or criminal justice
reform a national issue.

00:43:53.320 --> 00:43:56.450
I feel like it came up at the
end of Barack Obama's time,

00:43:56.450 --> 00:43:58.305
and then it was like
there's other issues.

00:43:58.305 --> 00:43:59.600
This goes back down.

00:43:59.600 --> 00:44:03.380
And then even pre-Barack Obama.

00:44:03.380 --> 00:44:08.990
But what is the
argument for really

00:44:08.990 --> 00:44:12.950
making this stuff a national
issue for Democrats,

00:44:12.950 --> 00:44:17.900
when it feels like everything
else is on fire right now?

00:44:17.900 --> 00:44:18.650
CHRIS HAYES: Yeah.

00:44:18.650 --> 00:44:22.520
I think it's hard to
get the oxygen for it

00:44:22.520 --> 00:44:25.520
as a national issue for
Democrats right now, frankly.

00:44:30.100 --> 00:44:32.950
There are these stories
that I tell myself on my way

00:44:32.950 --> 00:44:36.350
into work everyday,
like we're gonna

00:44:36.350 --> 00:44:38.960
get this in the goddamn
show if it kills me.

00:44:38.960 --> 00:44:41.485
And, like, nine times
out of 10, we don't.

00:44:41.485 --> 00:44:42.860
And then I go
home, and I'm like,

00:44:42.860 --> 00:44:46.130
I failed again to get
this thing in the show.

00:44:46.130 --> 00:44:47.690
And the other day,
I went in with--

00:44:47.690 --> 00:44:49.610
Sessions just issued
this sentencing memo.

00:44:49.610 --> 00:44:50.943
Are you guys familiar with this?

00:44:50.943 --> 00:44:52.470
Right.

00:44:52.470 --> 00:44:53.420
We got it in the show.

00:44:53.420 --> 00:44:56.250
And I was like--

00:44:56.250 --> 00:44:57.930
but that's a testament
to how hard it is

00:44:57.930 --> 00:45:00.090
to sort of treat these issues.

00:45:00.090 --> 00:45:01.600
My answer to that are twofold.

00:45:01.600 --> 00:45:04.110
One, the Democratic Party's
been incredibly complicit

00:45:04.110 --> 00:45:07.350
in the buildup of
the carceral state.

00:45:07.350 --> 00:45:09.690
And James Forman's book
is great about this.

00:45:09.690 --> 00:45:13.980
Washington DC, African
American Democratic leaders

00:45:13.980 --> 00:45:18.640
were part of building this up.

00:45:18.640 --> 00:45:21.930
The upside is that
most of this stuff

00:45:21.930 --> 00:45:24.870
is being driven
at a local level.

00:45:24.870 --> 00:45:29.230
In a tangible sense,
better funding

00:45:29.230 --> 00:45:32.410
for public defenders and better
prosecutors being elected

00:45:32.410 --> 00:45:35.350
in major cities
around America would

00:45:35.350 --> 00:45:38.470
have a more tangible
effect, most likely,

00:45:38.470 --> 00:45:41.107
in some ways than who
the attorney general is.

00:45:41.107 --> 00:45:42.940
Attorney general has a
huge amount of power.

00:45:42.940 --> 00:45:45.231
It matters a tremendous amount
that it's Jeff Sessions.

00:45:45.231 --> 00:45:49.090
That's not good for
reform of the system.

00:45:49.090 --> 00:45:54.400
But if Democrats focus and
focus in those environments--

00:45:54.400 --> 00:45:56.020
the Krasner case
is so fascinating

00:45:56.020 --> 00:45:58.060
because that's a primary.

00:45:58.060 --> 00:46:01.210
So focusing in the
context of places

00:46:01.210 --> 00:46:07.650
like Cy Vance in
Manhattan, Brooklyn DA,

00:46:07.650 --> 00:46:10.260
focusing on those
offices, there's

00:46:10.260 --> 00:46:11.590
a lot to be done at that level.

00:46:15.110 --> 00:46:17.155
TORRENCE BOONE: Last question.

00:46:17.155 --> 00:46:18.830
AUDIENCE: Thanks.

00:46:18.830 --> 00:46:21.557
Something I wonder--
what you think

00:46:21.557 --> 00:46:23.390
of the prospects of
trying to involve people

00:46:23.390 --> 00:46:26.150
around prosecution
or law enforcement,

00:46:26.150 --> 00:46:29.450
getting them more onboard
with criminal justice reform?

00:46:29.450 --> 00:46:31.700
And I think about this even
when I'm recounting, like,

00:46:31.700 --> 00:46:34.760
a local assembly
person who's very

00:46:34.760 --> 00:46:36.560
friendly with local
police, which is great.

00:46:36.560 --> 00:46:38.819
But it's easy to
get very pessimistic

00:46:38.819 --> 00:46:41.360
if I'm reading, say, personal
accounts or people in my friend

00:46:41.360 --> 00:46:42.860
circles who work
in law enforcement.

00:46:42.860 --> 00:46:45.470
And their perspective
is so far from where

00:46:45.470 --> 00:46:49.129
I can get to in terms of where
they think the problem is.

00:46:49.129 --> 00:46:50.670
CHRIS HAYES: That's
a great question.

00:46:50.670 --> 00:46:53.810
So I think there's been
some real progress on this.

00:46:53.810 --> 00:46:58.460
And I think that you've seen a
lot of police representatives

00:46:58.460 --> 00:47:03.230
come around on things like
decriminalization of marijuana,

00:47:03.230 --> 00:47:06.620
stuff like that, that
they used to oppose.

00:47:06.620 --> 00:47:09.325
If I'm not mistaken, I think
the professional organization

00:47:09.325 --> 00:47:12.860
of the American
Society of Prosecutors

00:47:12.860 --> 00:47:15.500
put out a critical statement
about the Sessions charging

00:47:15.500 --> 00:47:20.030
memo, which also was
amazing to me, which

00:47:20.030 --> 00:47:22.520
reflects this idea
that we don't actually

00:47:22.520 --> 00:47:24.000
think this is the way to go.

00:47:24.000 --> 00:47:28.230
So there's some light
and some space there.

00:47:28.230 --> 00:47:31.104
The other side of it is that--

00:47:31.104 --> 00:47:32.520
and again, to sort
of put yourself

00:47:32.520 --> 00:47:36.900
in the shoes of the people
that are manning the system--

00:47:36.900 --> 00:47:40.200
police particularly- and
this is true of prosecutors,

00:47:40.200 --> 00:47:42.390
particularly true of police--

00:47:42.390 --> 00:47:44.940
they're spending
all day every day

00:47:44.940 --> 00:47:48.540
interacting with people
that are in distress

00:47:48.540 --> 00:47:53.860
and are in their
worst situation.

00:47:53.860 --> 00:47:58.350
No one calls the cops
to bake them cookies.

00:47:58.350 --> 00:48:00.850
You call the cops when there's
distress and there's disorder

00:48:00.850 --> 00:48:03.010
and there's trauma.

00:48:03.010 --> 00:48:07.300
And there's a real taxing
effect psychologically

00:48:07.300 --> 00:48:10.450
on being introduced
to that all the time.

00:48:10.450 --> 00:48:12.700
Now, people will note,
rightly, that they're not

00:48:12.700 --> 00:48:14.194
the only people
that are introduced

00:48:14.194 --> 00:48:15.110
to that kind of thing.

00:48:15.110 --> 00:48:17.170
There are social
workers and child

00:48:17.170 --> 00:48:19.967
protective services workers
and emergency room doctors

00:48:19.967 --> 00:48:21.550
and all kinds of
people that are going

00:48:21.550 --> 00:48:26.600
through jobs in which they're
exposed to this all the time.

00:48:26.600 --> 00:48:28.690
But there's a psychological
toll, I think,

00:48:28.690 --> 00:48:32.680
it takes on everyone
involved in the system that

00:48:32.680 --> 00:48:34.930
is part of kind of
reproducing that punitiveness.

00:48:34.930 --> 00:48:37.600
And I don't know the
solution for that.

00:48:37.600 --> 00:48:41.890
But I think it is important
to have empathy for that

00:48:41.890 --> 00:48:44.110
as a psychological toll.

00:48:44.110 --> 00:48:46.480
There's a lot of sort of
trauma through osmosis

00:48:46.480 --> 00:48:48.830
that's happening.

00:48:48.830 --> 00:48:55.090
And cops are lied to all
the time, constantly.

00:48:55.090 --> 00:48:59.050
And it's easy to think
everyone's a liar.

00:48:59.050 --> 00:49:00.670
All of that--

00:49:00.670 --> 00:49:03.024
I don't know the solution
and whether that's a training

00:49:03.024 --> 00:49:04.690
solution, whether
that's the sort of way

00:49:04.690 --> 00:49:10.096
that we think about the
profession of policing.

00:49:10.096 --> 00:49:11.470
But it's a real
thing what you're

00:49:11.470 --> 00:49:13.420
saying, when you talk
about that perspective.

00:49:13.420 --> 00:49:16.750
There's a real thing
about police culture

00:49:16.750 --> 00:49:21.770
that is really deeply
viscerally opposed to reform.

00:49:21.770 --> 00:49:24.772
And that's something that
has to be dealt with.

00:49:24.772 --> 00:49:26.230
TORRENCE BOONE: So
we're incredibly

00:49:26.230 --> 00:49:29.110
action-oriented and passionate
about making a difference.

00:49:29.110 --> 00:49:32.300
That's what characterizes
the culture of our company.

00:49:32.300 --> 00:49:35.620
What else can we do,
other than engagement

00:49:35.620 --> 00:49:38.805
in the political process,
which you've covered?

00:49:38.805 --> 00:49:40.430
CHRIS HAYES: I mean,
I think, actually,

00:49:40.430 --> 00:49:41.763
that's the most important thing.

00:49:41.763 --> 00:49:44.660
I mean, the point
of this book is

00:49:44.660 --> 00:49:47.810
there are political
situations in America

00:49:47.810 --> 00:49:52.430
that were essentially the
product of special interests.

00:49:52.430 --> 00:49:57.620
Like the bankruptcy bill
was not some big democratic

00:49:57.620 --> 00:50:02.880
mobilization to make
bankruptcy harder for debtors.

00:50:02.880 --> 00:50:06.592
That was basically written in
a backroom by bank lobbyists.

00:50:06.592 --> 00:50:08.550
That's not true of the
criminal justice system.

00:50:08.550 --> 00:50:10.770
That was democratically
brought about in election

00:50:10.770 --> 00:50:15.270
after election for assembly,
counsel, state senate, city

00:50:15.270 --> 00:50:18.840
council, governor, district
attorney, attorney general,

00:50:18.840 --> 00:50:21.540
senator, Congress,
election after election,

00:50:21.540 --> 00:50:23.250
banging that drum of fear.

00:50:23.250 --> 00:50:25.170
And it only is
going to be unmade

00:50:25.170 --> 00:50:26.730
through democratic means.

00:50:26.730 --> 00:50:30.740
It's not going to be unmade
through policy conferences

00:50:30.740 --> 00:50:31.820
and think tanks.

00:50:31.820 --> 00:50:34.617
The policy solutions are there.

00:50:34.617 --> 00:50:36.700
What has to change
fundamentally are the politics.

00:50:36.700 --> 00:50:38.199
